[[File:Nissan NAPS logos.JPG|thumb|Nissan NAPS badge from [[Nissan Violet]] 1600GL (A10)]] '''NAPS''' stands for '''N'''issan '''A'''nti '''P'''ollution '''S'''ystem<ref>Datsun1200 Club - Tech Wiki - EGR</ref> a moniker used in Japan to identify vehicles built with emission control technology. The technology was installed so that their vehicles would be in compliance with Japanese Government [[Emission standard#Japan|emission regulations]] passed in 1968. The term was first introduced in Japan, with an externally mounted badge on the trunk of vehicles equipped. Nissan's implementation began with the [[Nissan Y engine|Y44E]] V8 engine installed in the [[Nissan President]] along with all vehicles installed with the [[Nissan L engine]] and the [[Nissan A engine]] in 1975. The initial introduction of Nissan's technology was the installation of an [[exhaust gas recirculation]] valve, followed with the addition of a [[catalytic converter]] and an air pump that added oxygen into the exhaust to promote higher temperatures in the catalytic converter, thus cleaning the exhaust further.
The NAPS-Z technology, introduced in 1978, was developed with assistance from [[Hitachi]].<ref>Yamaguchi, Jack K., "Japan: Reluctant Number One", World Cars 1981: 66</ref> It uses a novel implementation of two spark plugs per cylinder, called [[dual ignition]] together with electronically controlled fuel injection, installed on the [[Nissan Z engine]]. This terminology is often confused with the engine installed in the [[Nissan 280Z]], which used the "L" engine. However, the NAPS technology was installed in the Fairlady/Z and sold internationally.
Another version of the [[dual ignition|twin spark plug]] method was introduced on the [[Nissan Stanza]] with the [[Nissan CA engine|CA engine]], called NAPS-X, which eventually replaced the NAPS-Z approach. The CA engine implemented a hemispherical cylinder head, an approach used by several auto makers.
